Introduction

Understanding the patterns of mortality among young adults is crucial for shaping global health policies and interventions. This analysis focuses specifically on deaths in the 20‚Äì24 age group, utilizing global data from 1990 to 2021. By examining geographical patterns, identifying countries with the highest burden, observing long-term trends, and exploring country-specific variations, we gain critical insights into youth health risks and areas requiring focused attention. The following visualizations aim to present these findings clearly and support evidence-based decision-making.

Choropleth World Map of Deaths Aged 20‚Äì24

The choropleth map provides a global overview of deaths among individuals aged 20 to 24 years in 2021.
Higher concentrations are observed in countries like India, Nigeria, and parts of Africa, highlighting regional disparities in youth mortality.
This distribution reflects variations in healthcare access, education, socio-economic conditions, and public health systems across different regions.

Code 
import geopandas as gpd
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

map_data = pd.read_csv("indicator 1.csv")
map_data.columns = map_data.columns.str.strip()

map_filtered = map_data[(map_data['time_period'] == 2021) & (map_data['sex'] == 'Total')]

world = gpd.read_file("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/datasets/geo-countries/master/data/countries.geojson")

merged = world.merge(map_filtered, left_on='ISO3166-1-Alpha-3', right_on='alpha_3_code', how='left')

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(18,10))
merged.plot(column='obs_value', cmap='YlOrRd', linewidth=0.8, ax=ax, edgecolor='0.8', legend=True)
plt.title('Deaths Aged 20‚Äì24 by Country (2021)', fontsize=20)
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

Top 10 Countries by Deaths (Bar Plot)

The bar chart highlights the top 10 countries with the highest number of deaths aged 20 to 24 in 2021.
India and China lead significantly, reflecting their large population sizes and the associated challenges in public health management.
Nigeria, Pakistan, and Brazil also feature prominently, emphasizing the impact of healthcare and socio-economic factors on youth mortality rates.

Code 
top10 = (
    map_filtered
    .groupby('country')['obs_value']
    .sum()
    .sort_values(ascending=False)
    .head(10)
    .reset_index()
)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
sns.barplot(data=top10, x='obs_value', y='country', palette='Blues_r')
for index, value in enumerate(top10['obs_value']):
    plt.text(value + 2000, index, f'{value:,}', va='center')
plt.title('Top 10 Countries by Deaths (Aged 20‚Äì24) - 2021', fontsize=16, weight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Number of Deaths')
plt.ylabel('Country')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Global Deaths Over Time (Line Graph)

The line graph shows the trend of global deaths among youth aged 20 to 24 over the past three decades.
While the overall trend is downward, indicating improvements in healthcare, education, and living standards,
certain periods reflect stagnations or slight increases, possibly linked to regional conflicts, epidemics, or socio-economic disruptions.

Code 
global_data = map_data[(map_data['sex'] == 'Total') & (map_data['indicator'] == 'Deaths aged 20 to 24')]
global_deaths = global_data.groupby('time_period')['obs_value'].sum().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.plot(global_deaths['time_period'], global_deaths['obs_value'], marker='o', color='darkred')
plt.title('Global Deaths (Aged 20‚Äì24) Over Time (1990‚Äì2021)', fontsize=16, weight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Deaths')
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Top 10 Countries by Deaths (Scatter Plot)

The scatter plot represents the top 10 countries by deaths aged 20 to 24 in 2021, using both color and bubble size to indicate magnitude.
Larger bubbles like India and Nigeria highlight countries with a significantly higher burden,
while smaller bubbles represent relatively lower mortality among the top-ranked nations.
This visualization emphasizes relative differences within the top 10 group.

Code 
scatter_data = map_filtered.sort_values(by='obs_value', ascending=False).head(10)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,7))
sns.scatterplot(
    data=scatter_data,
    x='obs_value',
    y='country',
    hue='obs_value',
    palette='coolwarm',
    size='obs_value',
    sizes=(100, 400)
)
plt.title('Top 10 Countries by Deaths (Aged 20‚Äì24) - Scatter Plot (2021)', fontsize=16, weight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Number of Deaths')
plt.ylabel('Country')
plt.legend(title='Deaths', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Conclusion

This analysis of UNICEF youth mortality data provides important insights into global patterns of deaths among individuals aged 20 to 24 years.
The choropleth map illustrated significant regional disparities, with higher mortality concentrated in developing nations.
The bar chart and scatter plot highlighted that countries such as India, China, Nigeria, and Pakistan have the highest burden of youth deaths.
Meanwhile, the global time series graph demonstrated a positive long-term trend with an overall decrease in youth mortality rates over the past three decades.

Despite improvements, significant challenges remain, especially in regions affected by socio-economic instability, healthcare limitations, and population pressures.
Targeted interventions focusing on health access, education, and youth development are critical to further reducing mortality in this vulnerable age group.
This analysis emphasizes the need for global collaboration to achieve sustainable development goals (SDGs) related to health and well-being.
